<DOC><DOCNO> AP890624-0043 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 0457EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea     06-24 0233</FIRST><SECOND>PM-South Korea,0238</SECOND><HEAD>Boat People Allowed Temporary Stay, Given Instant Noodles</HEAD><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Immigration officials will let 78Vietnamese refugees stay temporarily in South Korea after theyburned their vessel at sea to force authorities to take them ashore,news reports said.   The officials initially said the Vietnamese would be given a newboat and towed back out to sea, the reports said Friday. But theylater decided the 45 men and 33 women could stay on Sangdo Islandoff the south coast until their burned boat is repaired, the reportssaid.   The boat people burned their boat at sea on June 17.   South Korea says its only refugee camp is already overcrowded andthe boat people cannot stay. The government said 1,057 Vietnameseboat people have been resettled in third countries since the 1975communist takeover in Vietnam. But 219 are awaiting resettlement.   Local villagers have also objected to the presence of thenewcomers. About 100 villagers in 16 fishing vessels blocked patrolboats carrying the refugees for five hours Thursday in an effort toprevent them from landing, according to Yonhap, the South Koreannews agency.   It said the villagers called off the protest after immigrationofficials promised the Vietnamese stay would be limited to 30 days.   The refugees were given five tents, 10 boxes of instant noodles,rice, medicine, T-shirts, pants, towels and soap, Yonhap said.</TEXT></DOC>